<br>
Perhaps if FDR had thought that it would be convenient busywork to keep a bunch of americans employed through the Great Depression, he might have funded Goddard as part of his <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>New Deal</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->l.<br>
<br>
This is really no more unlikely than all the other mostly useless programs that were initiated for the same reason, but this one might have yielded dividends greater than a simple-minded politician might have initialy realized. <br>
<br>
I wonder what the chronology of our space program might look like today if such a thing had happened. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 5:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=28.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Goddard</span><hr size=1> I suppose nuclear rockets would have been more likely. Consider that after going through WWII and building the first Atomic weapons, we probably would have asked the engineers and physicists that worked in the Manhattan project to also design a rocket based on atomic power if it had been a high priority.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1045<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 7:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=28.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Goddard</span><hr size=1> Goddard's biggest problem was his own personality. He refused to cooperate with anyone. He was secretive and private.<br>
<br>
From astronautix.com <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> ... Secretive, working in isolation, unwilling to work in the necessary large industrial teams required for the new technology, he solved all the fundamental problems of guided rockets - but his work represented a dead end. Parallel work by Von Braun in Germany and at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena duplicated his discovereis and led to post-war rocketry in Russia, Europe, and America.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->From the National Air and Space Museum:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Goddard's name was well known to the rocket experimenters of the 1920's-40's but due to his secretive nature and reluctance to share his work, which was very advanced for the times, his impact upon main developments was limited.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->From space.edu at Univ of North Dakota:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Robert H. Goddard...<br>
 His great feats were overcome by an almost fanatical desire for secrecy and his unwillingness to share his discoveries with any other scientists interested in rocket flight. Robert Goddard was to be the last &quot;mad scientist&quot; working by himself or with one or two other colleagues to accomplish rocket flight. <br>
...<br>
 it resolved him to keep all of his work more secret than previously to avoid such public scorn.<br>
...<br>
Goddard was almost paranoid about his work and very secretive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The Nazis supported rocketry, in part, because of restrictions based on other technologies.<br>
